data.content:
## What Breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the EF Core Cosmos DB provider allowed synchronous operations via an opt-in flag (e.g., `EnableSyncOverAsync()`). **In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), that opt-in is removed entirely.** Calling any synchronous LINQ operator (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) or `SaveChanges()` on the Cosmos provider now throws an `InvalidOperationException` at runtime — with no way to suppress it.

## The Fix

Convert all synchronous calls to their async equivalents:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- The underlying Cosmos DB SDK is async-only; sync support was always a compatibility shim.
- You'll need to propagate `async/await` up through your call chain (controllers, services, etc.).
- Remove the `EnableSyncOverAsync()` configuration from your `DbContext` setup — it's no longer recognized and will cause a build error.
